'''Child Soldiers International''',&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=https://www.child-soldiers.org/our-strategy-1|title=Child Soldiers International {{!}} Our strategy|website=www.child-soldiers.org|access-date=2016-10-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161015000232/https://www.child-soldiers.org/our-strategy-1|archive-date=2016-10-15|url-status=dead}}&lt;/ref&gt; formerly the '''Coalition to Stop the Use of Child Soldiers''', was a UK-based non-governmental organization that worked to prevent the recruitment, use and exploitation of children by armed forces and groups. As of 07 June 2019, it is no longer operational.&lt;ref&gt;https://twitter.com/childsoldiersin&lt;/ref&gt;

==Vision==

Child Soldiers International envisions a world where all children grow up realising their full potential and enjoying all their human rights. For this to be possible, Child Soldiers International is working to prevent armed forces and groups from recruiting, using and exploiting children.

==History==
Formerly the Coalition to Stop the Use of Child Soldiers,&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=https://www.child-soldiers.org/who-we-are-1|title=Child Soldiers International {{!}} Who we are|website=www.child-soldiers.org|access-date=2016-10-24}}&lt;/ref&gt; Child Soldiers International was founded in 1998 by leading human rights and humanitarian organisations, including Human Rights Watch, Amnesty International and Save the Children. Its purpose was to campaign for the adoption of the Optional Protocol to the Convention on the Rights of the Child on the involvement of children in armed conflict (OPAC)&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=http://www.ohchr.org/EN/ProfessionalInterest/Pages/OPACCRC.aspx|title=Optional Protocol to the Convention on the Rights of the Child|website=www.ohchr.org|access-date=2016-10-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130502015246/http://www.ohchr.org/EN/ProfessionalInterest/Pages/OPACCRC.aspx|archive-date=2013-05-02|url-status=dead}}&lt;/ref&gt; – a human rights treaty that prohibits the use of children in armed conflict and raises the age of military recruitment. The treaty was adopted in 2000 and entered into enforcement phase on 12 February 2002. Child Soldiers International continues to promote adherence to the Optional Protocol and other relevant human rights standards.

Since then, Child Soldiers International has continued to promote the adoption and implementation of international legal standards&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=https://www.child-soldiers.org/international-standards|title=Child Soldiers International {{!}} International standards|website=www.child-soldiers.org|access-date=2016-10-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180220033316/https://www.child-soldiers.org/international-standards|archive-date=2018-02-20|url-status=dead}}&lt;/ref&gt; protecting children from military recruitment or use in hostilities.

==Priority Countries==
Child Soldiers International has a London headquarters and conducts research, advocacy and capacity building in countries across the world. Recent programmes have included: [[Central African Republic]];&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=https://www.child-soldiers.org/central-african-republic|title=Child Soldiers International {{!}} Central African Republic|website=www.child-soldiers.org|access-date=2016-10-24}}&lt;/ref&gt; Democratic Republic of Congo;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=https://www.child-soldiers.org/democratic-republic-of-congo|title=Child Soldiers International {{!}} Democratic Republic of Congo|website=www.child-soldiers.org|access-date=2016-10-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180308231442/https://www.child-soldiers.org/democratic-republic-of-congo|archive-date=2018-03-08|url-status=dead}}&lt;/ref&gt; Afghanistan;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=https://www.child-soldiers.org/afghanistan|title=Child Soldiers International {{!}} Afghanistan|website=www.child-soldiers.org|access-date=2016-10-24}}&lt;/ref&gt; India;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=https://www.child-soldiers.org/india|title=Child Soldiers International {{!}} India|website=www.child-soldiers.org|access-date=2016-10-24}}&lt;/ref&gt; Myanmar;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=https://www.child-soldiers.org/myanmar|title=Child Soldiers International {{!}} Myanmar|website=www.child-soldiers.org|access-date=2016-10-24}}&lt;/ref&gt; Thailand;&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=https://www.child-soldiers.org/thailand|title=Child Soldiers International {{!}} Thailand|website=www.child-soldiers.org|access-date=2016-10-24}}&lt;/ref&gt;

==Policy making==
Child Soldiers International delivers research findings and policy recommendations to the [[United Nations Security Council]] in New York and the UN [[Committee on the Rights of the Child]] in Geneva, Switzerland. According to UN documents, in relation to the adoption and enforcement of the [[Optional Protocol on the Involvement of Children in Armed Conflict]], Child Soldiers International plays &quot;a key role in ensuring implementation at every level.&quot;

==Publications==
Child Soldiers International and [[UNICEF]] published the ''Guide to the Optional Protocol to the Convention on the Rights of the Child''&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=http://www.unicef.org/sowc06/pdfs/option_protocol_conflict.pdf|title=Guide to the Optional Protocol to the Convention on the Rights of the Child|last=|first=|date=|website=|publisher=|access-date=}}&lt;/ref&gt; in December 2003. The guide summarizes the process of the treaty's adoption, its fundamental provisions, and recommends that certain activities be undertaken to ensure its full enforcement. It is a practical tool written to aid other NGOs, humanitarian groups, and legislative bodies in implementing OPAC's standards.

In 2001, 2004 and 2008, Child Soldiers International published ‘Child Soldiers Global Reports’ which provide a snapshot of the child soldier situation in every country worldwide. In 2012, Child Soldiers International published Louder than words: an agenda for action to end state use of child [[soldiers]],&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=https://www.child-soldiers.org/shop/louder-than-words|title=Child Soldiers International {{!}} Louder Than Words|website=www.child-soldiers.org|access-date=2016-10-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161024231449/https://www.child-soldiers.org/shop/louder-than-words|archive-date=2016-10-24|url-status=dead}}&lt;/ref&gt;  accompanied by a practical 10-point checklist to assist states to end their recruitment of children. In 2016, Child Soldiers International published A law unto themselves? Confronting the recruitment of children by armed groups. This provides a legal analysis of progress made so far in engaging with armed groups about child recruitment and use.

Child Soldiers International continues to regularly publish research, analysis and recommendations&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=https://www.child-soldiers.org/pages/shop/department/all|title=Child Soldiers International {{!}} All|website=www.child-soldiers.org|access-date=2016-10-24}}&lt;/ref&gt; to support its advocacy goals. These seek to inform policy and action by building understanding of the causes of child soldier recruitment and use, and identifying sustainable solutions.

==Funding and organisational structure==
Child Soldiers International is a UK registered charity (registered charity number 1095237), with section 501(c)(3) public charity status in the USA.  Direct donations are welcomed&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=https://www.child-soldiers.org/donate/where-ever-the-need-is-greatest/5/credit-card|title=Child Soldiers International {{!}} Donate - Donate now|website=www.child-soldiers.org|access-date=2016-10-24}}&lt;/ref&gt; from individuals, and provide an essential source of support.

Annual audited financial statements&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=https://www.child-soldiers.org/annual-accounts|title=Child Soldiers International {{!}} Annual accounts|website=www.child-soldiers.org|access-date=2016-10-24}}&lt;/ref&gt; are filed with the UK Charity Commission,&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=http://apps.charitycommission.gov.uk/showcharity/registerofcharities/RegisterHomePage.aspx|title=About Charities|last=Wales|first=The Charity Commission for England and|website=apps.charitycommission.gov.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-10-24}}&lt;/ref&gt; Companies House,&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/organisations/companies-house|title=Companies House  - GOV.UK|website=www.gov.uk|access-date=2016-10-24}}&lt;/ref&gt; and published on Child Soldiers International's own website.  For the 2015-16 financial year Child Soldiers International had an annual income of £623,588 and expenditure of £604,832. In 2015-16, 94% of expenditure supported programme activities (6% of expenditure supported the costs of generating funds).

Child Soldiers International operates with a small staff team, bringing in specialist consultancy support where needed. Programmatic work is delivered in close collaboration with local and national organisations&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=https://www.child-soldiers.org/who-we-work-with|title=Child Soldiers International {{!}} Who we work with|website=www.child-soldiers.org|access-date=2016-10-24}}&lt;/ref&gt; in target countries.  Job vacancies&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=https://www.child-soldiers.org/work-for-us|title=Child Soldiers International {{!}} Work for us|website=www.child-soldiers.org|access-date=2016-10-24}}&lt;/ref&gt; are advertised on the organisational website. The organisation is governed by a board of trustees.&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|url=https://www.child-soldiers.org/our-board|title=Child Soldiers International {{!}} Our board|website=www.child-soldiers.org|access-date=2016-10-24}}&lt;/ref&gt;

