Today, Mount Fuji is an international destination for tourism and [[Mountaineering|mountain climbing]].&lt;ref name=&quot;climbing&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.ibarakijets.org/guides/fujiguide.pdf | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090327032252/http://www.ibarakijets.org/guides/fujiguide.pdf | archivedate=March 27, 2009 | title=Climbing Mount Fuji? route maps|pages= 4–5 |date= |access-date=December 23, 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.christmaswhistler.web44.net/adventure/mtFuji.html|title=Climbing Mt. Fuji travel log|publisher=ChristmasWhistler|date=June 30, 2002}}&lt;/ref&gt; In the early 20th&amp;nbsp;century, populist educator [[Frederick Starr]]'s [[Chautauqua]] lectures about his several ascents of Mount Fuji—1913, 1919, and 1923—were widely known in America.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news
