==Geography==
{{Multiple image
| align = 
| direction = 
| total_width = 400
| image1 = MtFuji_FujiCity.jpg
| alt1 = 
| caption1 = Mount Fuji seen from [[Fuji, Shizuoka]]
| image2 = Chuurei-tou_Fujiyoshida_17025277650_c59733d6ba_o.jpg
| caption2 = Arakurayama Sengen Park and the Chūrei-tō pagoda in [[Fujiyoshida, Yamanashi]]
}}

Mount Fuji is a very distinctive feature of the [[geography of Japan]]. It stands {{cvt|3776.24|m|ft|0}} tall and is located near the Pacific coast of central Honshu, just southwest of Tokyo. It straddles the boundary of [[Shizuoka Prefecture|Shizuoka]] and [[Yamanashi Prefecture|Yamanashi]] [[Prefectures of Japan|Prefectures]]. Four small cities surround it: [[Gotemba, Shizuoka|Gotemba]] to the east, [[Fujiyoshida]] to the north, [[Fujinomiya, Shizuoka|Fujinomiya]] to the southwest, and [[Fuji, Shizuoka|Fuji]] to the south. It is surrounded by five lakes: [[Lake Kawaguchi]], [[Lake Yamanaka]], [[Saiko Lake|Lake Sai]], [[Lake Motosu]] and [[Lake Shōji]].&lt;ref name=&quot;gvp&quot;&gt;{{cite gvp|vnum=0803-03=|title=Fuji}}&lt;/ref&gt; They, and nearby [[Lake Ashi]], provide views of the mountain. The mountain is part of the [[Fuji-Hakone-Izu National Park]]. It can be seen more distantly from Yokohama, Tokyo, and sometimes as far as [[Chiba (city)|Chiba]], [[Saitama (city)|Saitama]], [[Tochigi, Tochigi|Tochigi]], [[Ibaraki, Ibaraki|Ibaraki]] and [[Lake Hamana]] when the sky is clear. It has been photographed from space during a space shuttle mission.&lt;ref name=&quot;sts-107&quot;&gt;{{cite web|url=http://spaceflight.nasa.gov/gallery/images/shuttle/sts-107/html/s107e05690.html|title=STS-107 Shuttle Mission Imagery|publisher=[[NASA]]|date=January 26, 2003|access-date=December 16, 2012}}&lt;/ref&gt;

